SIMPLE: hatchet
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hatchet
<hw>Hatch"et</hw> <pr>(-⟦ecr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>hachette</ets>, dim. of <ets>hache</ets> ax. See 1st
<er>Hatch</er>, <er>Hash</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small ax with a
short handle, to be used with one hand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically, a tomahawk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Buried was the bloody <qex>hatchet</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 674 pr=JMD --></p>

<p><cs><col><b>hatchet face</b></col>, <cd>a thin, sharp face, like the
edge of a hatchet</cd>; hence: <col><b>hatchet-faced</b></col>,
<cd>sharp-visaged.</cd> <au>Dryden.</au> -- <col><b>To bury the
hatchet</b></col>, <cd>to make peace or become reconciled.</cd> --
<col><b>To take up the hatchet</b></col>, <cd>to make or declare war.
The last two phrases are derived from the practice of the American
Indians.</cd></cs></p>

<p><ent>hatchet man</ent>⟦br⟧
